Frequency (40 MHz):
This is the number of cycles or events that occur in one second. In this case,
there are 40 million cycles per second.

Period (25 ns):
This is the duration of a single cycle. The relationship is expressed by the
formula: Period = 1 / Frequency.
*   1 / 40,000,000 Hz = 0.000000025 seconds
*   0.000000025 seconds = 25 x 10⁻⁹ seconds = 25 nanoseconds (ns).

https://www.ni.com/docs/en-US/bundle/labview-myrio-toolkit/page/myriohelp/myrio_fpga_clock.html
The FPGA target on the hardware has a clock rate of 40 MHz, which means the
clock cycle is 25 ns. To generate a frequency that is less than 40 MHz, you can
change a signal on every x number of rising edges of the clock signal. The
following figure shows an example of changing a 40 MHz clock signal on rising
edges to generate 20 MHz and 10 MHz clock signals, respectively.

High-Energy Physics:
In experiments like the one at CERN, 40 MHz indicates that proton bunches
collide every 25 ns, a high frequency crucial for data collection and analysis.

Electronics and FPGAs:
In a 40 MHz system, any code within a single-cycle timed loop (SCTL) on an FPGA
must execute within 25 ns, a critical factor for designing and timing circuits.

Component Timing:
If a chip has a required 25 ns execution time at a 40 MHz clock, it means the
chip can operate reliably within the 25 ns cycle time of the clock.

