"25ns 40 Mhz" indicates that a 40 MHz clock has a period of 25 nanoseconds,
meaning that a single clock cycle is 25 nanoseconds long. This relationship is a
fundamental concept in digital electronics, particularly in systems like the LHC
at CERN where proton bunches collide every 25 ns due to the 40 MHz frequency,
and in FPGA design where the clock cycle determines the execution time of
operations.

